        <TextView
            android:layout_width="match_parent"
            android:layout_height="match_parent"
            android:text="Paleozoic Era: Took place from around 541 to 252 million years ago. The Paleozoic Era was a time of many striking changes for Earth’s climate, geology, and natural life. Split into 6 geologic periods, each of brought along further change and diversity to multiple parts of Earth, the Paleozoic remains the era in which life became prominent and diversified.
•	Cambrian: (541-485 mya) The age of multiple celled life and aquatic armored arthropods. The period of the boom in evolution.
•	Ordovician: (485-440 mya) The age of the first primitive fish, cephalopods, and coral.
•	Silurian: (440-415 mya) The age of mass evolution of jawless fish into primitive jawed fish.
•	Devonian: (415-360 mya) The age of the fish. This period boasted a huge array of more diverse fish. The first amphibians evolved.
•	Carboniferous: (360-300 mya) The age of giant amphibians, insects, and arachnids. This period was mostly swamp at the time with the first reptiles evolving.
•	Permian: (300-250 mya) The age of mammal-like reptiles. This period was very dry at the time.

"
